                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Collapse Patterns -->
        <section class="concept-section reveal delay-1">
          <h2>The Same Structure, Every Time</h2>
          <p>
            The Bronze Age Collapse. The fall of Rome. The Black Death. The 2008 financial crisis.
            Strip away the surface details and the same seven-stage pattern emerges every time.
            This is what Nefertari saw. This is what both networks have been fighting about for
            three thousand years: can the pattern be interrupted, or is it baked into the physics
            of complex systems?
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 1: The Optimization Trap</h3>
          <p>
            Everything gets more efficient. Redundancy is eliminated. Supply chains tighten.
            Knowledge specializes. Every node becomes essential. The system has never worked
            better—and has never been more fragile.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 2: Warning Signs Dismissed</h3>
          <p>
            Small failures occur. Isolated incidents, they're called. A pattern recognition
            specialist in a Bronze Age temple sees the connections. A geneticist in a modern
            lab notices impossible data. Nobody listens. They never do.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 3: The First Domino</h3>
          <p>
            One critical node fails. Could be plague, invasion, financial collapse, engineered
            bioweapon—the specific trigger matters less than the network's structure. Every
            system that depended on that node begins to fail.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 4: Positive Feedback</h3>
          <p>
            Now the collapse accelerates itself. Refugees spread chaos. Trade routes sever.
            Food systems break. Governments lose legitimacy. Each failure triggers the next.
            The spiral becomes self-sustaining.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 5: The Threshold</h3>
          <p>
            The point of no return. Even if the original trigger is resolved, the cascade
            continues under its own momentum. After this, there is no recovery—only survival
            and rebuilding.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 6: Selection</h3>
          <p>
            Massive death. Knowledge loss. Infrastructure destroyed. The Order's prepared
            bloodlines retreat to safe zones. The defensive network's carriers attempt to
            preserve what they can. Natural selection operates at civilization scale.
          </p>

          <h3>Stage 7: Reset</h3>
          <p>
            Survivors rebuild at lower complexity. The Order breeds the best candidates. The
            defensive network re-embeds methodology in new cultural forms. Two hundred to five
            hundred years later, the cycle begins again.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-top: 24px; padding-top: 24px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border);">
            The genesis question: Can human beings interrupt Stage 3 before it hits Stage 5?
            Or is the pattern something deeper than human choice—a property of complexity
            itself? Nefertari believed intervention was possible. Amenhotep believed it was
            a comforting illusion. Thirty-two centuries later, neither has been proven wrong.
          </p>
        </section>

